preds:
Current prior is overwhelmingly strong given the very short timeframe of prediction, and that historical volatility of percentage changes in positivity on Sunday / Monday are notably low, possibly due to changes in number of tests. From discussion with teammates, a model using mean / std dev. of percentage changes in positivity over the past 10 days yields a strong distribution for 11-15 states; the probability of outliers in the 6-10 bin or 16-20 bin are too small to exceed a 1% threshold. Given the timeframe and the fact that we are forecasting a rolling average, which somewhat negates extreme fluctuations, I think it doesn't make sense to use a bottoms-up / Fermi-ization approach, but rather to identify the magnitude of very extreme outliers / highly improbable event data that can shift forecast from the prior; may update if something big happens, but nothing that would fit the description so far in the news.  From NYT's state-level policies on reopening (https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/states-reopen-map-coronavirus.html?auth=login-email&login=email):
Texas, Florida, Kansas, Arkansas are states currently above 10% taking reversal measures or states very close to the 10% margin;
Georgia, Nebraska, Utah, Wisconsin, Minnesota are states currently below 10% that have reopened and have the best chance of increasing above 10%.
